abstract: Some older adults are dabbling in this powerful psychedelic, which is mostly illegal in the United States.
snippet: Some older adults are dabbling in this powerful psychedelic, which is mostly illegal in the United States.
lead_paragraph: At 74, the venture capitalist George Sarlo might not have seemed an obvious candidate for an ayahuasca experience. Mr. Sarlo, a Hungarian Jewish immigrant who arrived in the United States in 1956, has had great professional success as the co-founder of Walden Venture Capital. He lives in an upscale San Francisco neighborhood, in a large house with an unobstructed view of the Golden Gate Bridge.

headline_main: Elton John’s Bookshelves Are Meticulous. Just Ask Him.

abstract: The performer in chief is forcing us to live in a B-movie horror.
snippet: The performer in chief is forcing us to live in a B-movie horror.
lead_paragraph: Readers of this page have every reason to be suspicious of the political musings of an actor. I’m suspicious of them myself. But consider this: Our politics and our press are completely dominated by an entertainer president. In recent weeks we’ve even read about our ex-reality-show host president discussing foreign policy over the phone with the ex-TV comedian president of Ukraine.

headline_main: A Novel of Jamaica Brimming With Magic, Passion and History

abstract: From Ta-Nehisi Coates to Terese Marie Mailhot to Imani Perry, writers are letting their audiences eavesdrop on private conversations. Parul Sehgal asks what it means.
snippet: From Ta-Nehisi Coates to Terese Marie Mailhot to Imani Perry, writers are letting their audiences eavesdrop on private conversations. Parul Sehgal asks what it means.
lead_paragraph: The memoir, as we know it, was born out of an act of petty larceny. Late one night in the fourth century, a teenager plucked pears off a neighbor’s tree. He didn’t especially want them; he tasted a few and tossed the rest to the hogs. He stole them for the sake of stealing them. “It was foul, and I loved it,” he later wrote. “I loved my own undoing.”

abstract: We asked veterans of political debates for their reviews of each of the Democratic hopefuls onstage Tuesday.
snippet: We asked veterans of political debates for their reviews of each of the Democratic hopefuls onstage Tuesday.
lead_paragraph: Before Tuesday’s Democratic primary debate, we asked political debate coaches and experts to tell us what each candidate needed to do to have a good night. Here’s that story. Today, we asked the experts how the candidates did.

abstract: Media companies merged to take on tech, and tech giants are producing media. Edmund Lee, a media reporter, has his eyes on what comes next.
snippet: Media companies merged to take on tech, and tech giants are producing media. Edmund Lee, a media reporter, has his eyes on what comes next.
lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? Edmund Lee, a media reporter, discussed the tech he’s using.

headline_main: Save Some Popcorn for the Deal-Making Behind TV
headline_print_headline: When Will a Tech Giant Swallow a Media Giant?

abstract: “Catch and Kill” was pulled from two of Australia’s biggest online book retailers amid legal threats from the former National Enquirer editor who features prominently in the book.
snippet: “Catch and Kill” was pulled from two of Australia’s biggest online book retailers amid legal threats from the former National Enquirer editor who features prominently in the book.
lead_paragraph: SYDNEY, Australia — Two of Australia’s biggest online booksellers have suspended sales of Ronan Farrow’s new book after one of the men who is prominent in it threatened legal action.

abstract: Elections that offer voters no choice provide cover for authoritarian leaders to chip away at democracies in Eastern Europe and Central Asia.
snippet: Elections that offer voters no choice provide cover for authoritarian leaders to chip away at democracies in Eastern Europe and Central Asia.
lead_paragraph: MOSCOW — As a rolling group of protesters occupied streets in central Moscow this past July, a liberal opposition newspaper published a photograph of a young woman blocked by the police at a steel barricade. The sign she held up read, “I have the right to a choice.”
